9. Plasticity Rules

9.1 Standardized Rules

NIMCP defines standard plasticity behaviors:

9.1.1 Hebbian
Δw = η * pre_activity * post_activity
w(t+1) = w(t) + Δw - λ * w(t) // with decay


9.1.2 Spike-Timing-Dependent Plasticity (STDP)
if pre_spike_time < post_spike_time:
Δw = A_plus * exp(-(post_time - pre_time) / τ_plus)
else:
Δw = -A_minus * exp(-(pre_time - post_time) / τ_minus)


9.1.3 Oja's Rule (with normalization)
Δw = η * (pre * post - post² * w)


9.1.4 BCM (Bienenstock-Cooper-Munro)
θ = moving_average(post_activity)
Δw = η * pre * post * (post - θ)


9.2 Plasticity Parameters

SET_PLASTICITY_RULE {
  link_id: LinkID,
  rule_type: "stdp",
  parameters: {
    A_plus: 0.01,
    A_minus: 0.01,
    tau_plus: 20.0,  // ms
    tau_minus: 20.0,
    max_weight: 1.0,
    min_weight: 0.0
  }
}

9.3 Meta-Plasticity

Learning rates can adapt based on network state:
- High error: Increase learning rate
- Stable performance: Decrease learning rate
- Novel inputs: Temporarily increase plasticity

10. Clustering and Specialization

10.1 Cluster Formation

Nodes self-organize into functional clusters:

CLUSTER_ANNOUNCE {
  cluster_id: ClusterID,
  specialization: FeatureCode,
  member_nodes: [NodeID],
  hub_nodes: [NodeID],  // Inter-cluster connectors
  density: float,  // Internal connectivity
  activity_profile: {
    mean_spike_rate: float,
    synchrony_index: float,
    dominant_frequencies: [float]
  }
}

10.2 Specialization Evolution

Clusters develop through:
1. Feature affinity - nodes processing similar features strengthen connections
2. Temporal correlation - synchronized nodes cluster together
3. Functional pressure - task demands shape cluster boundaries

10.3 Cross-Cluster Integration

Hub nodes maintain connections across clusters:
- Higher connection limits
- Broader feature subscriptions
- Special routing privileges
- Translation between feature domains

