14. Partition Handling and Recovery

14.1 Partition Detection

Local indicators:
- Heartbeat failures
- Route table shrinkage
- Echo timeout patterns
- Sudden activity drops

PARTITION_DETECTED {
  detecting_node: NodeID,
  lost_nodes: [NodeID],
  remaining_neighbors: [NodeID],
  detection_confidence: float
}

14.2 Adaptation During Partition

Nodes adjust behavior:
- Increase local connectivity
- Lower activation thresholds
- Cache important routes
- Boost discovery beacons

14.3 Recovery Protocol

On reconnection:

RECOVERY_SYNC {
  partition_id: PartitionID,
  nodes_recovered: [NodeID],
  topology_delta: TopologyUpdate,
  feature_remapping: FeatureMap
}

Recovery steps:
1. Exchange topology updates
2. Reconcile feature namespaces
3. Gradually increase traffic
4. Reweight connections
5. Merge cluster information

15. Security Considerations

15.1 Authentication

Control messages can be signed:
signature = HMAC-SHA256(message_content, shared_secret)


15.2 Authorization

Node capabilities:
- Feature namespace access
- Cluster membership
- Routing privileges
- Control message types

15.3 Attack Mitigation

- Rate limiting per connection
- Anomaly detection
- Spike storm prevention
- Feature code validation
- Confidence score verification

16. Implementation Guidelines

16.1 Minimum Compliance

To claim NIMCP 2.0 compliance:
- Support Event Packet format
- Implement at least one plasticity rule
- Handle basic Control Messages
- Provide subscription mechanism

16.2 Reference Implementation

Suggested architecture:
Node {
event_queue: PriorityQueue<EventPacket>
control_queue: Queue<ControlMessage>
connections: Map<NodeID, SynapticLink>
routing_table: RoutingTable
subscriptions: FeatureSubscriptions
plasticity_engine: PlasticityEngine
}

16.3 Performance Considerations

- Event Packets: Optimize for low latency
- Control Messages: Batch when possible
- Plasticity updates: Asynchronous computation
- Route caching: LRU with decay

